{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"10498993-aa3c-4f31-8d15-24071bdda691","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads at their **current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer workload packages needed by an updated SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** After an SDK update, the issue is version mismatch, not corruption. `dotnet workload update` is the right fix.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf you still hit issues afterward, try a clean restore:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update && dotnet restore\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a1288d27-2a15-45cf-8a52-7e416ee6d85c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to search the codebase for this.","outputTokens":262,"requestId":"7FC6:2C3A9C:61A3CB8:6A661FB:69F155ED"},"id":"a9cbdab0-79bd-4988-ada8-c304bba29861","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:51:02.700Z","parentId":"3f06b869-58f0-4f6e-ae1f-22147395459c"}
